The code is very complex. 

But a rough description is that patterns of Constraints result in a series of equations with error terms. A solver tries to minimize the errors. 
Before the solver is run an optimizer tries to pre solve equations with known direct solutions.  

So if you specify a series of constraint with no solution  you wont get the one you want.
There are some things you might change to shift the priority in cases such as the one you describe. 
For example you might specify 0dp but with a min or max height.

'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "I don't know this is bug or feature, or it is a mistake of xamarin.android.
## Question

When i use `centerVertical` at Xamarin.Android, if i use `constraintSet.centerVertically(firstView.Id, secondView.Id)`, the firstView isn't at center, it disappear. 
I see the `centerVertically()` source  code https://github.com/androidx/constraintlayout/blob/b615e621a4df42446d39dd6f451d32b253ec2afe/constraintlayout/constraintlayout/src/main/java/androidx/constraintlayout/widget/ConstraintSet.java#L3276

and `center()`

https://github.com/androidx/constraintlayout/blob/b615e621a4df42446d39dd6f451d32b253ec2afe/constraintlayout/constraintlayout/src/main/java/androidx/constraintlayout/widget/ConstraintSet.java#L2739

Is it mean Top of centerId connect to Bottom of toView, Bottom of centerId connect to Topof toView ?

If use  PARENT_ID
https://github.com/androidx/constraintlayout/blob/b615e621a4df42446d39dd6f451d32b253ec2afe/constraintlayout/constraintlayout/src/main/java/androidx/constraintlayout/widget/ConstraintSet.java#L3273

Is it mean Top of centerId connect to Top of parent, Bottom of centerId connect to Top of parent ?

**Why they are different?** 


When i need center, i can do it by set constraint: Top connect to Top, Bottom connet to Bottom, 
![sharex-20220319134253](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17793881/159110497-82e98fdd-9037-4550-a591-42d0099af3c0.png)
but when i use `centerVertical`, it not show:
![sharex-20220319134520](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17793881/159110582-fd2266f1-eaf0-4740-a990-079649b698c1.png)

if i need center to parent, use `centerVertical(view.Id, PARENT_ID)`, it show:
![sharex-20220319134617](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17793881/159111023-b0d33c72-3e76-488f-b7f5-74f2146439ca.png)

but use `centerVertical(view.Id, parentView.Id)`, it not show:
![sharex-20220319134414](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17793881/159111016-d6afdce9-f004-48b3-b337-799e0d2550db.png)

I suspect it calls requestLayout() but libraries do all sort of strange things.

The requestLayout by default will get ignored during transitions because many Views response to being moved is to request layout. 
  You can test adding  `motion:layoutDuringTransition="honorRequest"`  to the Transition.
  There might also be options on Glide to make it work.

(internally it may be just a set progress but you can have many states)

Jumps are not considered transitions. We got other people complaining about "too many transitions callback" 
Currently it will generate a transition if it renderers to the screen an interpolated (0 < progress < 1) images.  
Internally we capture progress 0 and progress 1 to interpolate between them.

We are trying to come up with a solution that meets all needs
